<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,618,1075]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,502,726,751]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Distribution and habitat.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[512,722,726,751]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brasiliensis">
<emphasis box="[512,722,726,751]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Anolis brasiliensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is typical from open areas of central 
<collectingCountry box="[1160,1228,726,751]" name="Brazil" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[1246,1314,726,751]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1830,1852]" captionTargetBox="[155,1436,303,1787]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,303,1808]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 1. Distribution of examined material of Anolis auratus, A. bombiceps and A. brasiliensis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/234981/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Fig. 
<number box="[1301,1314,727,751]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
), and it is known from the states of Pará, Tocantins, Maranhão, Piauí, Ceará, Mato Grosso, Goiás, Minas Gerais, São Paulo, and in the Distrito Federal. In the Brazilian Amazonia it occurs on open vegetation enclaves at southern Pará and northern Mato Grosso states. The occurrence in Santa Cruz do Arari, Marajó 
<collectingCountry box="[1087,1158,834,859]" name="Iceland" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Island</collectingCountry>
, is considered doubtful (specimen 
<collectionCode box="[276,374,871,895]" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/tids-e3wr" name="University of Brasilia Herpetological Collection" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">CHUNB</collectionCode>
08803). The Emílio Goeldi Museum has a great collection from the Marajó 
<collectingCountry box="[1268,1339,870,895]" name="Iceland" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Island</collectingCountry>
, and for decades has been inventorying the region and do not found the species. The other reason is the large geographic distance to the closest known record in the Amazonian border with Cerrado. 
<taxonomicName box="[1028,1237,942,967]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brasiliensis">
<emphasis box="[1028,1237,942,967]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Anolis brasiliensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is predominantly terrestrial and diurnal, inhabits gallery forest, igapó (seasonally flooded forest), and savanna areas nearby forests, where it is mainly found on the leaf litter and on tree trunks (rarely more than one meter above ground—Vanzolini &amp; 
<bibRefCitation author="Williams" box="[180,348,1050,1075]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" refString="Vanzolini, P. E. &amp; Williams, E. E. (1970) South American anoles: the geographic differentiation and evolution of the Anolis chrysolepis species group (Sauria, Iguanidae). Arquivos de Zoologia, 19, 1 - 298. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.11606 / issn. 2176 - 7793. v 19 i 3 - 4 p 125 - 298" type="journal article" year="1970">
Williams 
<number box="[288,348,1051,1075]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="1970.0">1970</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Vitt" box="[359,546,1050,1075]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" refString="Vitt, L. J., Shepard, D. B., Vieira, G. H. C., Caldwell, J. P., Colli, G. R. &amp; Mesquita, D. O. (2008 b) Ecology of Anolis nitens brasiliensis in cerrado woodlands of Cantao. Copeia, 2008, 144 - 153. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1643 / CP- 06 - 251" type="journal article" year="2008" yearSuffix="b">
Vitt 
<emphasis box="[408,464,1050,1075]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[471,531,1050,1075]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="2008.0">2008</number>
b
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
